{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37290d19-052a-4cb6-9fdd-4de54de09940","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_lOOsKRXKB1SAv1fe8y1QJr","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Explaining C# 13 breaking changes"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_eTdLIJC4VZlxZ2oUxPJpSe","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-646cbbc213e84ae29e9186f07e9af565/migrated","description":"Create output directory","initial_wait":5},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create output directory"}],"interactionId":"6bed82c3-352c-44c1-84ac-0c2813322cc4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about specific C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 prohibits `InlineArray` on `record struct` types. The fix is to change it to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in a local function inside an iterator: C# 13 now allows `stackalloc` in iterator methods (in local functions that don't yield), but actually the breaking change is the opposite - in C# 12, `unsafe` code in iterators was not allowed in certain contexts. \n\nLet me reconsider the iterator rules more carefully. The key distinction is whether a local function within an iterator can use `stackalloc` or `unsafe` contexts - C# 13 appears to have changed how it validates these scenarios, likely becoming stricter about what's permitted in iterator methods even within nested local functions. So the breaking change is that `unsafe` context no longer flows from the containing class into local functions within iterators—the local function needs its own `unsafe` modifier to use `stackalloc` or other unsafe operations. The fix is straightforward: mark the local function as `unsafe` explicitly. Now I'm looking at the next issue with collection expressions in Resolver.cs where `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` have new behavior in C# 13.\n\nThe problem is that an empty collection expression `[]` has become ambiguous in overload resolution because it can now target both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, whereas in C# 12 it would resolve to a single overload. The fix is to explicitly specify which type you want, either by using `ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty` or by casting the collection expression directly.","outputTokens":1089},"id":"70949444-4cd4-4404-aa10-9231557a7470","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:10:51.543Z","parentId":"09be0f9d-6874-4571-8eb2-682cb8414875"}
